  "story_title": "awards-index",
  "review_text": "[SPAN: display=block; fontsize=extralarge; fonttype=bold; text= Awards Index]\n\nThis section serves as the official \"What to Expect in a Year‑End Summary\" for each publication year of Marvel Comics.\n\nIn no particular order, here's what a Year-End-Summary does:\n[HANG] * lays out some basic statistical data\n[HANG] * lists significant company changes\n[HANG] * recalls the most important debuts\n[HANG] * remembers the top moments\n[HANG] * celebrates the triumphs\n[HANG] * laments ultimate failure in the form of the Trash Heap of the Year Award\n[HANG] * hangs its head in disgust in the form of the Shaft Award\n[HANG] * lists dangling plot threads and notable blunders\n[HANG] * honors artistic covers, panels and top cliff-hangers\n[HANG] * recalls letters that were either outstanding or revealed child-like innocence\n[HANG] * chuckles once more at the best belly-laugh moments\n[HANG] * remembers the most touching scenes or issues\n[HANG] * points out the best and worst things of the year, along with noticeable trends\n[HANG] * provides a title analysis (in later years)\n[HANG] * never forgets that Marvel was, first and foremost, a <i>business</i>\n\nIn short, the Year‑End Summary gathers the whole year into one place, offers closing thoughts, and wonders aloud (with everyone else) what the <i>next</i> year holds in store as we look ahead!\n\nNot <i>every</i> year will contain every category, particularly in the early going where there is far less material to cover.&nbsp; But as mid-1960s Marvel kicks into gear, award opportunities become more numerous, with more chances to [SPAN: severity=success; text=shine] (and... to [SPAN: severity=error; fonttype=italic; text=offend]).\n\nNote that the Vintage Moment Award is uniquely a <i>monthly</i> award, with simply too many to generalize across an entire year.&nbsp; It is listed below for the sake of completeness, though you will not see it the end of the year -- only at the end of each publication <i>month</i>.\n\nMost awards follow a consistent pattern:\n[HANG] * a list of finalists (because <i>nothing</i> good should go unmentioned),\n[HANG] * a crowned winner,\n[HANG] * an occasional tip-of-the-hat Honorable Mention when something deserves a nod even if it didn't <i>quite</i> take home the trophy.\n\nBelow is a general description of the award categories\n\n[DIVIDER]\n[SPAN: fontsize=large; fonttype=bold; text= AWARD CATEGORIES (ALPHABETICAL)]\n\n<b>Artistic Bail-Out Award</b>\n[BR] For those issues whose plots are on life support, but the artist swoops in, grabs the paddles, yells \"<i>CLEAR</i>,\" and jolts the story into something worth looking at.\n\n<b>Best and Worst Things to Happen to Marvel This Year</b>\n[BR] A reflection on the single <i>best</i> development of the year -- and the single <i>worst</i> -- whether editorial, creative, structural, or accidental.\n\n<b>Best Back-Up Story</b>\n[BR] Especially relevant in the early years, when anthology books regularly featured short tales.&nbsp; This award honors the best of those secondary offerings.\n\n<b>Best Belly-Laugh Moment</b>\n[BR] The funniest moment of the year, intentional or otherwise.&nbsp; Marvel's Silver Age was full of them.\n\n<b>Best Credit Box</b>\n[BR] A Longbox Playback specialty.&nbsp; When the Bullpen got playful, the credit boxes became their own art form.\n\n[SPAN: severity=success; fontsize=larger; fonttype=bold; text=Best Story of the Year]\n[BR] The crown jewel.&nbsp; The issue that best represents Marvel's storytelling potential for that calendar year.\n\n<b>Biggest Blunder</b>\n[BR] For continuity errors, logic failures, editorial oversights, or other face-plant moments that make you stare at the page and wonder, \"Did someone even <i>read </i>this?\"\n\n<b>Biggest Surprise of the Year</b>\n[BR] The issue that shocked you by being far better, deeper, stranger, or more emotionally resonant than expected.\n\n<b>Missed Opportunity Award</b>\n[BR] For the panel, plot beat, or artistic choice that had all the ingredients for greatness... and still managed to underwhelm.\n\n[SPAN: severity=error; fontsize=larger; fonttype=bold; text=Shaft Award]\n[BR] This award recognizes the story that most egregiously betrays reader trust -- through laziness, incoherence, or outright disrespect.\n\nIt's called the Shaft Award because the story doesn't just <i>fail</i> - [SPAN: severity=error; text=it gives its readers the <i>shaft</i>] -- violating the unspoken contract between Marvel and anyone brave enough to turn the page.\n\nA story so heinously offensive that even granting it the Trash Heap of the Year Award seems like letting it off easy - it <i>demands</i> its own category for its crimes against readership.&nbsp; The one that makes you want to <i>throw something</i> (preferably that issue).\n\n<b>Spiral Award</b>\n[BR] It's called the Spiral Award because the story doesn't merely ramp up - it <i>spirals completely out of control</i>, collapsing under the weight of its own increasingly unhinged decisions.\n\nFor plots that don't just escalate -- they <i>detonate</i> -- rocketing into full-blown mayhem faster than you can blurt out, \"Wait... <i>WHAT</i>?\" or \"How did we get <i>here</i>?\"&nbsp; Sometimes they're so unintentionally bad, they deliver hilarity for all the wrong reasons.\n\n<b>Title Analysis</b>\n[BR] Introduced in 1966, this section ranks the year's ongoing features by average grade, revealing which titles soared and which limped across the finish line.\n\n<b>Top Cliff-Hangers</b>\n[BR] The most effective \"come back next month\" endings -- the ones that made readers in the 1960s stare at the final panel in disbelief and mutter, \"<i>Holy cliff-hanger, Batman!</i>\"\n\n<b>Top Covers</b>\n[BR] The most iconic or striking covers of the year, whether for composition, drama, or sheer audacity.\n\n<b>Top Panels</b>\n[BR] The single best visual storytelling moments -- the panels that linger long after the issue is closed.&nbsp; The ones that made you <i>wish</i> you had another copy of the issue so you could cut them out and pin them to your wall.\n\n<b>Touching Moments</b>\n[BR] Emotional beats that landed with sincerity, poignancy, or unexpected depth.\n\n[SPAN: severity=error; fontsize=larger; fonttype=bold; text=Trash Heap of the Year Award]\n[BR] The worst of the worst.&nbsp; The issue that sinks below all others in quality, coherence, or execution, and becomes a cautionary tale for future generations.&nbsp; The one that makes you question your life choices and wonder if you'll ever dare plunk down money again for the chance to read this title.\n\n<b>Trope of the Year</b>\n[BR] The narrative pattern, storytelling crutch, or recurring motif that most dominated Marvel's output for that calendar year -- whether intentionally, accidentally, or hilariously.\n\n<b>Vintage Moment Award</b>\n[BR] A monthly award celebrating the most perfect moment that instantly reminds you when these stories were first published -- the charm, weirdness, now-dated technology, or \"They actually printed <i>that</i>?\" storytelling moments that defined the era.&nbsp; <i>Far</i> too frequent to crown on a yearly basis and thus provided with many Monthly Summaries."
}